 r 9th lord of MacGregor於大約1190年出生在英國蘇格蘭時，他的父親Lord John Eoin MacGregor32歲，母親Christian Campbell32歲。他和Lady Marion Filean de Gilchrist至少有1個兒子。他去世於大約1229年享年41歲。"},"zh-hans":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1229":"大约1190年–大约1229年","1190–1229":"1190年–1229年","1212–Male":"1212年–殁","1190–1300":"1190年–1300年","1220–1285":"1220年–1285年","1160–1229":"1160年–1229年","1160–Female":"1160年–殁","1190":"1190年","1300":"1300年","1212":"1212年","1220":"1220年","1285":"1285年","1160":"1160年","Abt 1229":"大约1229年","Abt 1190":"大约1190年","1229":"1229年","Scotland":"苏格兰","lifeSummary":"当William Dougeal MacGregor r 9th lord of MacGregor于大约1190年出生在英国苏格兰时，他的父亲Lord John Eoin MacGregor32岁，母亲Christian Campbell32岁。他和Lady Marion Filean de Gilchrist至少有1个儿子。他去世于大约1229年享年41岁。"},"hr":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1229":"oko 1190.–oko 1229.","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1212–Male":"1212–preminuo","1190–1300":"1190–1300","1220–1285":"1220.–1285","1160–1229":"1160–1229","1160–Female":"1160–preminula","1190":"1190","1300":"1300","1212":"1212","1220":"1220.","1285":"1285","1160":"1160","Abt 1229":"oko 1229.","Abt 1190":"oko 1190.","1229":"1229","Scotland":"Scotland"},"cs":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1229":"okolo 1190–okolo 1229","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1212–Male":"1212–Zesnulý","1190–1300":"1190–1300","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1160–1229":"1160–1229","1160–Female":"1160–Zesnulá","1190":"1190","1300":"1300","1212":"1212","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1160":"1160","Abt 1229":"okolo 1229","Abt 1190":"okolo 1190","1229":"1229","Scotland":"Scotland"},"da":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1229":"omkring 1190–omkring 1229","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1212–Male":"1212–Afdød","1190–1300":"1190–1300","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1160–1229":"1160–1229","1160–Female":"1160–Afdød","1190":"1190","1300":"1300","1212":"1212","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1160":"1160","Abt 1229":"omkring 1229","Abt 1190":"omkring 1190","1229":"1229","Scotland":"Skotland"},"nl":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1229":"circa 1190–circa 1229","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1212–Male":"1212–Overleden","1190–1300":"1190–1300","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1160–1229":"1160–1229","1160–Female":"1160–Overleden","1190":"1190","1300":"1300","1212":"1212","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1160":"1160","Abt 1229":"circa 1229","Abt 1190":"circa 1190","1229":"1229","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1229":"about 1190–about 1229","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1212–Male":"1212–Deceased","1190–1300":"1190–1300","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1160–1229":"1160–1229","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1190":"1190","1300":"1300","1212":"1212","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1160":"1160","Abt 1229":"about 1229","Abt 1190":"about 1190","1229":"1229","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacGregor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McGregor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McGregor","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Griogair</b> or <b>Mac Greagair</b> ‘son of <i>Griogar</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name   Gregory  . Compare   Grierson  .","History: The Scottish Highland clan McGregor claims descent from the king of Picts and Scots Kenneth MacAlpin (Cináed mac Ailpín; 810–858  AD ). The origins of the clan are unclear. In the 13th century it was established on lands on the shores of Loch Awe and already in conflict with its neighbors of Clan Campbell. By the 16th century the McGregors had retreated deep into Glen Strae and acquired the nickname ‘Children of the Mist’. In 1603 the clan was abolished by royal edict and many members of the clan changed their surname. A year later, the chief of Clan McGregor and eleven of his followers were hanged in Edinburgh. Despite the proscription, the clan survived and supported the king in the Scottish Civil War (1644–51). The exploits of the Jacobite leader Rob Roy McGregor (1671–1734) were romanticized in a novel by Sir Walter Scott. The proscription was eventually repealed in 1774."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Dougeal","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Dubhghall ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dubhghall","meanings":["Gaelic: from <i>dubh</i> ‘black, dark’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was a byname applied to Danes, in contrast to the fairer Norwegians and Icelanders (  compare  Fionnghall  )."]},{"name":"Dugal","meanings":["Gaelic: from <i>dubh</i> ‘black, dark’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was a byname applied to Danes, in contrast to the fairer Norwegians and Icelanders (  compare  Fionnghall  )."]},{"name":"Dugald","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Dubhghall .  The final <i>-d</i> is due to a mishearing of the Gaelic form, in which the final <i>-ll</i> sounds like <i>-ld</i> to English ears."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Dougeal MacGregor r 9th lord of MacGregor was born about 1190, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Lord John Eoin MacGregor, was 32 and his mother, Christian Campbell, was 32. He had at least 1 son with Lady Marion Filean de Gilchrist. He died about 1229, at the age of 41."},"et":{"Abt 1190–Abt 1229":"umbes 1190–umbes 1229","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1212–Male":"1212–Surnud","1190–1300":"1190–1300","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1160–1229":"1160–1229","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1190":"1190","1300"